<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="165" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,261,972]" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,333,360]" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: SVL Min/Max (14.18/ 
<quantity box="[586,672,333,360]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
), midbody scales 33–41 (x̅ 36.8), four or five loreal scales (also in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="King" authorityYear="1962" box="[151,256,370,396]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvus">
<emphasis box="[151,256,370,396]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. parvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, contrasting with five or six in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[611,762,369,396]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis box="[611,762,369,396]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stejneger" authorityYear="1904" box="[818,1012,369,396]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandisquamis">
<emphasis box="[818,1012,369,396]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. grandisquamis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), two or three postmental scales (two in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[181,332,405,432]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis box="[181,332,405,432]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stejneger" authorityYear="1904" box="[347,542,405,432]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandisquamis">
<emphasis box="[347,542,405,432]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. grandisquamis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="King" authorityYear="1962" box="[605,710,406,432]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvus">
<emphasis box="[605,710,406,432]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. parvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), a low number of dorsal body scales from axilla to groin (15 to 18, differing from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="King" authorityYear="1962" box="[361,465,442,468]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvus">
<emphasis box="[361,465,442,468]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. parvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stejneger" authorityYear="1904" box="[521,716,441,468]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandisquamis">
<emphasis box="[521,716,441,468]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. grandisquamis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except 
<emphasis box="[804,951,441,468]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">
S. g. 
<taxonomicName box="[861,951,441,467]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="stibarus">stibarus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
[14–16 scales]). Males dorsal head pattern absent or very faint except a dull parietal spot (
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A." box="[684,985,477,504]" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" pagination="193 - 260" refId="ref23344" refString="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A. (1966) Sphaerodactylus (Gekkonidae) in the greater Puerto Rico region. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 10, 193 - 260." type="journal article" year="1966">Thomas &amp; Schwartz 1966</bibRefCitation>
); males with no pigmentation on throat, females with throat pattern; males from 
<collectingRegion box="[614,703,513,539]" country="Puerto Rico" name="Culebra" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">Culebra</collectingRegion>
might have some pigmentation on the throat; males with red to yellow head; males and females with reduced scapular patch; males and females with dorsal lines stippled; males dorsal pattern salt and pepper; females with medial lines fused to form a blotch or imperfect line; shortened snout. SVL is smaller in specimens from West 
<collectingRegion box="[594,683,621,647]" country="Puerto Rico" name="Culebra" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">Culebra</collectingRegion>
(Min= 
<quantity box="[760,876,621,648]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.404" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" unit="mm" value="14.04">14.04 mm</quantity>
, Max= 
<quantity box="[953,1067,621,648]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6879999999999997" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" unit="mm" value="26.88">26.88 mm</quantity>
) than in specimens from 
<collectingRegion box="[1346,1436,621,647]" country="Puerto Rico" name="Vieques" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">Vieques</collectingRegion>
(Min= 
<quantity box="[223,339,657,684]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.418" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" unit="mm" value="14.18">14.18 mm</quantity>
, Max= 
<quantity box="[418,501,657,684]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,261,972]" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,693,720]" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">Color in life</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[359,442,693,719]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1615,1640]" captionTargetBox="[175,1414,1003,1577]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[164,1424,993,1589]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 11. Live specimens of Sphaerodactylus inigoi from Vieques (A, female and B, male) and Culebra Island, Flamenco beach (C, female and D, male)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3586977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3586977/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
): Female: ground color fluctuates from tan to gray, head and tail fluctuates from gray to light brown, head pattern well defined, medial lines forming a blotch, ocelli color pale or yellowish. Male ground color fluctuates from gray to light brown, head red-orange with absent head pattern or faint remains of it (e.g. parietal or nuchal spot). Iris color brown, copper, or orange.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,261,972]" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">
The color of female 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Daza &amp; Pinto &amp; Thomas &amp; Herrera-Martinez &amp; Scantlebury &amp; Padilla García &amp; Balaraman &amp; Perry &amp; Gamble" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Daza &amp; Pinto &amp; Thomas &amp; Herrera-Martinez &amp; Scantlebury &amp; Padilla García &amp; Balaraman &amp; Perry &amp; Gamble" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[432,526,838,864]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="inigoi">
<emphasis box="[432,526,838,864]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. inigoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to the female coloration of 
<emphasis box="[956,1095,838,864]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. g. mimete</emphasis>
s, while the male coloration is more similar to the males of 
<emphasis box="[485,610,873,900]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. g. ateles</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Padilla, L. F." box="[627,776,873,900]" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" refId="ref21580" refString="Padilla, L. F. (2006) Geographic variation in color pattern on Sphaerodactylus macrolepis Gunther 1859, (Sauria: Gekkonidae). M. Sc. Thesis, University of Puerto Rico, San Juan. 153 pp." type="book" year="2006">Padilla 2006</bibRefCitation>
), although the former has a marked head, unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Daza &amp; Pinto &amp; Thomas &amp; Herrera-Martinez &amp; Scantlebury &amp; Padilla García &amp; Balaraman &amp; Perry &amp; Gamble" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Daza &amp; Pinto &amp; Thomas &amp; Herrera-Martinez &amp; Scantlebury &amp; Padilla García &amp; Balaraman &amp; Perry &amp; Gamble" baseAuthorityYear="1966" box="[1341,1436,874,900]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="inigoi">
<emphasis box="[1341,1436,874,900]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="165">S. inigoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males, where the pattern is absent or very faint.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
